of home, the assembled essays tease out the links between the past and present, with a hopeful longing for various futures. Filipino Studies makes bold declarations about the productive frameworks that open up new archives and innovative landscapes of knowledge for Filipino and Filipino American Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFilipino AmericansxStudy and teaching. 0aFilipinosxMigrationsxStudy and teaching. 0aFilipinosxStudy and teaching. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectsxStudy and teachingzPhilippines. 0aNationalismxStudy and teachingzPhilippines. 0aNeoliberalismxStudy and teachingzPhilippines. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aEspiritu, Augusto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aManalansan, Martin F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479829415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479829415.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK